# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1904-chicago-white-sox-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The **1904 Boston Americans season** was the fourth season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 95 wins and 59 losses, 1+1⁄2 games ahead of the New York Highlanders.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans were set to play the National League (NL) champion New York Giants in the 1904 World Series; however, the Giants refused to play.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 7 home runs and had 84 RBIs, and Freddy Parent with a .291 batting average.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 40 complete games with a 26–16 record and 1.97 ERA, while striking out 200 in 380 innings.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (23–14) and Jesse Tannehill (21–11).
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; September 13 at Philadelphia, September 14 vs.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Both ties against New York were the second games of doubleheaders.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Note: Stats in brackets are derived from Retrosheet which differ from the stats found on MLB.com.
[src:1904-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1904 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 34th season of the Braves franchise.
